    <item>
      <title>Candles</title>
      <link>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/random/stray-thoughts/2024-06-09-candles/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 09 Jun 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/random/stray-thoughts/2024-06-09-candles/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I was driving north on Greenmount and noticed that the traffic lights at many intersections had stopped working. &amp;ldquo;Typical Baltimore,&amp;rdquo; was my first thought. Thankfully, it was Sunday morning, and the streets were empty, so it wasn&amp;rsquo;t too bad. If anything, I was pleasantly surprised to see everyone being civil and patiently waiting for others at the defunct lights. My destination turned out to be devoid of electricity as well. A tree had fallen nearby, taking down some electric wires with it. We sat in darkness, barely shielded from the sweltering heat outside.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Eye Test</title>
      <link>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/journal/life@jhu/eye-test/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 20 Jan 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/journal/life@jhu/eye-test/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I have had glasses ever since I was 10 years old. As a kid I used to wear really thick durable plastic frames, which evolved to metal frames in my teenage years, and then back to durable plastic frames in college. My power used to increase incessantly until I stopped growing and so I&amp;rsquo;ve probably paid a visit to an ophthalmologist every single year of my life in India. Today for the first time I went for an eye check-up in the US.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>An Area of Darkness</title>
      <link>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/notes/books/an-area-of-darkness/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 30 Dec 2017 09:20:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://apurvanakade.github.io/blog/notes/books/an-area-of-darkness/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;medium right&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.amazon.com/Area-Darkness-Discovery-India/dp/0375708359&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;img src=&#34;data:image/webp;base64,&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;An Area of Darkness&lt;/em&gt; is a disturbing pessimistic novel written by V.S. Naipaul about his first visit to India in 1962. This was India not too long after the Independence with it&amp;rsquo;s freshly minted Constitution, trying to make a transition from an English past to an Indian future. Naipaul shares the sentiments of West, the tone of the book is not unlike &lt;em&gt;Slumdog Millionaire&lt;/em&gt; (a very unpopular movie in India).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
